caption:
When I was a teenager I hated all of my freckles and pigmented spots – because I looked so different. Nobody else had them. Everybody was asking me why I have them and I couldn’t answer. I also didn’t know why I got more and more. I was sad and frightened when I discovered a new spot on my skin. Now a few years later I finally got the answer what those spots are and what causes them. My relationship to my body changed as well. I am now happy that my skin looks different and that I don’t look like everybody else. I love every spot and freckle on my skin and I’m always so excited when I discover a new one. I love how every body looks so different in their own way and nobody should be ashamed of it. It took me a while to learn it but it was worth it. ✨🐆

Some of you might have followed us along our story of renovation. It took us three months, every weekend, more paint than we could have ever imagined, the best friends in the world (more than 30 of them), a couple of beloved jeans, our fear of heights, and all the energy we had. We learned that a Gloria is necessary to remove wallpaper, you have to paint 3 to 4 times over doors and their frames, sanding your floors might cost you your hearing, you shouldn‘t leave the lights on in the back room, when painting your floors, that renovating is the best hangover cure, and that wallcolours are drying way faster when it‘s more than 30 degree! After three months, we were able to move in what we could really call OUR home. Because we build it (at least a bit of it) with our own hands, the sweat of our friends and maybe one or the other tear ;) It‘s definitely worth it! Would I do it again? If I had all the time in the world, maybe for my own house in Sicily. caption: So this is happening. We found a flat. We will renovate it. It‘s scary. But it‘s also cool somehow. Last weekend, we started by pulling down various layers of wall papers. We haven‘t finished, yet - they won. This week, we‘ll have a rematch and we‘re going to take care of the floors. Step by step.

Renovating Update: Four or five weekends ago (I can‘t even count them anymore), we got the keys to our new flat and started renovating right away.

What we managed to do so far is to get rid of around 7 layers of wallpapers within 3 rooms, to plaster the wholes in the walls, to sand the floorboards and the wall, clean everything over and over again and do many, many steps for preparations and inbetween. These are the results so far (Image 2-4 are the before, 5 & 6 are after or in between ;))

This weekend, we want to varnish the floorboards, put in the new floor in the soon-to-be living room and, if we manage, prime the raw stone walls. 

It‘s a lot and it‘s exhausting. It’s expensive. But it‘s also exiting and it‘s fun. So fingers crossed, we can move into our very own dream-flat in the beginning of August 🤞🏻

caption: No Stock-Image this time: We‘re looking for a flat in Berlin (like so many others) and will reward every hint with endless Spritz on our new balcony. But now to the situation in Berlin: unfortunately the housing-situation has become more and more impossible in Berlin because of the current Mietendeckel. The flats of renters, who moved out in the time between November and now, are not put on the market, because big housing-agencies and landlords rather let their flats be unoccupied for months, than miss the chance for some more money. The idea: Wait until the Mietendeckel (a law that regulates rent-prices to work against exorbitant prices) is declared as illicit, renovate the flat, and put it on the market for an insane price. This means literally no flats are on the market at the moment. Every flat we applied to so far got more than 1000 applications - mostly even up until 5000 - and this with thousands of vacant flats, that are just not on the market. This should be illegal. If you‘re living in a flat with crazy prices, you can try to get an abatement of rent with the Mietbremsen-law. Everyone please educate yourself about this topic and don‘t just take the situation for granted ❤️ it‘s not Berlin that is expensive, it‘s not normal to pay 15 euros per sqm, it‘s not normal that a Family with two kids can‘t afford a 4-room apartment, it‘s not normal that thousands of flats are empty rightnow - at least it shouldn‘t be!

caption: We don’t need fancy occasions to dress up- Life is a fancy occasion!!!!! 💎

Offen mit meinem Körper zu sein (auf sozialen Netzwerken, aber auch in real-life) ist meine Art meinen Körper zu akzeptieren und lieben zu lernen. In meinen Teenager-Jahren wurde mir (währenddem mein BMI bereits zu niedrig war) bereits von der Gesellschaft und von der Mode-brache vermittelt ich seie zu dick und müsse abnehmen. Auch heute noch, obwohl ich für Body-positivity stehe, und Frauen in allen Formen und Größen wunderschön finde, sagt mir mein Inneres Kind ich müsste mich für meine Hüften schämen, die zwanzigste Diät probieren und ich sei zu dick. 
Mich fotografieren zu lassen oder zu fotografieren, wenn ich mich in meinem Körper wohlfühle, ist mein Kampf gegen mein inneres Kind. Dass hier ist keine Erklärung und Entschuldigung, dass ist eine Aufforderung über niemanden zu urteilen, den du nicht kennst. Du hast nicht das Recht zu entscheiden wer billig ist, wer ein gutes oder schlechtes Selbstwertgefühl hat oder wer, warum, welche Sachen postet. Mein Körper meine Regeln. Mein Körper mein fight. Und jeder hat seine eigenen Regeln, Ziele und Absichten! #mybodymychoice #mybodymyrules #bodypositivity #bodyacceptance

caption:
Bikinis that only fit Victoria Secret models and have nothing to do with real life? No, thanks! On this picture I’m wearing a fast fashion bikini, that does not look too bad but felt uncomfortable, was not adjustable and definitely not water-, swim-, or jump-resistant - that’s why I’m looking like a showered poodle (crestfallen). We talked with a lot of different women and at least half of them felt similar. The swimwear industry counts on standardized norms and is far away from reality. A bikini usually ranges between the sizes of 35 to 52 or XS to XXL, though our bodies do not fit these measurements. When I‘m wearing a 34 bikini it fits perfectly at the bust but I‘m really lucky if it covers my nipples... to fit the bikinis that are currently on the market, you would either have to have small breasts and a small bust or big breasts and a big bust. I still can‘t get it in my head, how far away the market is from the reality of many women. Most bikinis are not adjustable, they are designed in a way that only size zero models can wear them even if they are available in bigger sizes and  they are definitely not made for swimming.  We want to change that: Instead of Male-Gaze and Size Zero, we're betting on you: Diverse women, their opinions and feelings - including head jump-safety, anti-boobie-flash-guarantee, muffin-top-awareness and a good feeling on the beach. 
We want to be your knights in shining sun milk armour, your Frida Kahlos and Wonder Women - we don't want to get confirmed what we think we already know. We really want to know what you need. We want to make the perfect bikini - for real women by real women. 
If you give us your next 5 minutes (tested confidentially ;)), we will give everything to make your saltwater-soaked summer dreams come true.  CHECK THE LINK IN MY BIO FOR THE SURVEY! AND PLEASE SHARE IT AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE! ❤️❤️❤️
